    <articletitle>
     Is subjective memory loss correlated with MMSE scores or dementia?
    </articletitle>
    <pagination>
     <medlinepgn>
      80-3
     </medlinepgn>
    </pagination>
    <abstract>
     <abstracttext label="OBJECTIVES" nlmcategory="OBJECTIVE">
      (1) To determine if subjective memory loss (SML) is associated with Mini-Mental State Examination (MMSE) scores, (2) to determine if this association persists after adjustment for other factors, and (3) to determine the sensitivity and specificity of SML for dementia.
     </abstracttext>
     <abstracttext label="POPULATION" nlmcategory="METHODS">
      1751 seniors sampled from a population registry.
     </abstracttext>
     <abstracttext label="MEASURES" nlmcategory="METHODS">
      Age, sex, education, SML, the MMSE, and the Center for Epidemiologic Studies-Depression (CES-D) scale. Dementia was diagnosed by clinical examination.
     </abstracttext>
     <abstracttext label="ANALYSIS" nlmcategory="METHODS">
      Linear regression models were constructed. The sensitivity and specificity of SML were determined with a diagnosis of dementia being the gold standard.
     </abstracttext>
     <abstracttext label="RESULTS" nlmcategory="RESULTS">
      SML was correlated with MMSE scores, even after adjusting for age, sex, education, and depressive symptoms. The sensitivity of SML was 0.58 (95% confidence interval [CI]: 0.45, 0.71), and the specificity was 0.76 (95% CI: 0.74, 0.78) for dementia.
     </abstracttext>
     <abstracttext label="CONCLUSIONS" nlmcategory="CONCLUSIONS">
      SML is correlated with MMSE score. However, SML is neither sensitive nor specific for dementia.
     </abstracttext>
    </abstract>
